n":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thornton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":26,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":35,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Thornton was born in 1189, in England, his father, Peter Thornton, was 35 and his mother, Margaret Eynion, was 35. He married Elizabeth in 1223, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1244, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1189–1244":"1189–1244","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1195–1227":"1195–1227","1224–1268":"1224–1268","1155–1254":"1155–1254","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1206":"1206","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1268":"1268","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1244":"1244","1254":"1254","1155":"1155","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1189–1244":"1189–1244","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1195–1227":"1195–1227","1224–1268":"1224–1268","1155–1254":"1155–1254","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1206":"1206","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1268":"1268","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1244":"1244","1254":"1254","1155":"1155","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1189–1244":"1189–1244","1185–Female":"1185–Décédée","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1195–1227":"1195–1227","1224–1268":"1224–1268","1155–1254":"1155–1254","1155–Female":"1155–Décédée","1206":"1206","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1268":"1268","1223":"1223","1189":"1189","1244":"1244","1254":"1254","1155":"1155","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert de Thornton est né en 1189, à Angleterre, son père, Peter Thornton, avait 35 ans et sa mère, Margaret Eynion, avait 35 ans. Il a épousé Elizabeth en 1223, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1244, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 55 ans."},"de":{"1189–1244":"1189–1244","1185–Female":"1185–Verstorben","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1195–1227":"1195–1227","1224–1268":"1224–1